POLIOMYELITIS UPDATE (10): ISRAEL (JERUSALEM) CIRCULATING VACCINE DERIVED POLIOVIRUS, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Mon 7 Mar 2022
Source: Haaretz [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
https://www.haaretz.co.il/misc/article-print-page/1.10658321


The head of public health services at the Ministry of Health, Sharon Elroi-Price, today [Mon 7 Mar 2022] referred to the case in Jerusalem where a 4-year-old girl with polio was diagnosed, saying that "there are at least tens or hundreds more infections (which are probably asymptomatic). We do not expect there to be a wave of children coming with symptoms, but we understand that the virus is spreading. A vaccinated child is protected."

In a conversation with journalists, Elroi-Price emphasized: "We are very far from an uncontrollable outbreak, we prevent it by locating those around the case and vaccinating the unvaccinated among them. Elroi-Price added that her office wants to "make sure that all the children, especially in the Jerusalem district, are in an optimal vaccination status, meaning they have undergone the complete childhood vaccination regime according to the recommendations of the Ministry of Health. Regarding polio, there are 4 vaccinations given during the first year of life. The current recommendations are to precede the first vaccination, momentarily only in the Jerusalem district, to 6 weeks and the 2nd one to 12 weeks of age, in order to make sure earlier protection is conferred.

She noted that the District Health Bureau and the Jerusalem Municipality are conducting an extensive investigation, and that a project manager has been recruited to locate the people who were in close contact with the child who was diagnosed with polio yesterday [Sun 6 Mar 2022], "extending the sampling of sewage to more locations within and around the focus for fecal cultures, to fence the area in question."

According to tests conducted on sewage by the Public health services in the Ministry, the polio virus is only found in the Jerusalem area.

Yesterday [Sun 6 Mar 2022], the Ministry of Health announced that a 4-year-old girl from Jerusalem had been diagnosed with polio, the first case in Israel since 1988. The girl has not been vaccinated against the virus as part of routine vaccinations. The girl was brought for treatment in Hadassah Ein Kerem. Prof. Shimon Reif, director of the children's department at the hospital said the initial suspicion was raised due to neurological symptoms like weakness in the leg muscles and other symptoms. "Tests conducted involving a pediatric neurologist confirmed that it was polio," Reif said. The girl was treated at the hospital for one week, and after her condition improved, she was transferred to rehabilitative treatment due to a muscular injury - a familiar phenomenon among polio patients.

The Ministry of Health also announced that the Jerusalem District Health Bureau has opened an epidemiological investigation, approaching contacts for specific guidance. According to the findings of the investigation further recommendations will be decided upon.

The polio strain that the girl was infected with is one of the strains found in the vaccine, which has been genetically modified and may cause disease in those who are not vaccinated against the virus. As far as is known, the infected girl developed symptoms manifested by weakness on one side of the body, but did not need to be hospitalized. The case was later discovered by the Ministry's performed routine monitoring of sewage in the area where the girl lives. Such a finding sometimes appears in the monitoring, but so far no cases of morbidity have been detected.

The polio vaccine is given in 4 doses, at the ages of 2, 4, 6 and 12 months of age. An additional booster is given at school at the age of 7. The vaccination rate, with the 4 doses among those born in 2020 in Jerusalem, is 83%, but there are areas where the vaccination rates are particularly low and stand at about 50%. The Ministry of Health is currently segmenting the population to concentrate efforts and vaccinate those who have not yet been vaccinated.

[Byline: Efrati Ido]

